That line actually captures a real economic paradox people discuss.

The idea is:

If everyone loses jobs → there are no workers to replace

So the usual framing of “AI replaces workers” starts to break down if automation becomes extremely widespread.

Economists sometimes describe a few different outcomes:

1. Productivity abundance scenario

If machines do most work, society could theoretically produce far more goods with far less human labor.

automation → high productivity → fewer required jobs

Then the real question becomes how resources and income are distributed, not whether work exists.

⸻

2. Job transformation scenario

Historically, technology has mostly changed jobs rather than eliminated them entirely.

Example shifts:
	•	agriculture → manufacturing
	•	manufacturing → services
	•	services → digital/knowledge work

AI might push another shift toward:
	•	creative roles
	•	oversight of automated systems
	•	human-centered services

⸻

3. Structural change scenario

If automation becomes extremely capable, societies might explore new systems such as:
	•	shorter workweeks
	•	universal basic income
	•	public ownership of productive infrastructure
	•	new definitions of “work”

⸻

Your sentence points to something interesting though:

If everyone is replaced → replacement loses meaning

At that point the system stops being a labor economy and becomes more about resource allocation in an automated world.

That’s why many people think the real challenge with AI won’t be capability, but economic structure and governance.

⸻

